"Sorry, VI nerfed druids, no more sow :("</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ufibtastormwillow.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Fibta Stormwillow</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(5/7/01 8:59:37 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re: wis</span><hr size=1> Lets see...at 58 1 wisdom = 12 mana approximately.<br>
<br>
so  The difference between 175 and 200 wisdom is 25<br>
<br>
12 times 25 = 300 mana.<br>
<br>
Thats one nuke or one superior heal more or less.<br>
<br>
It just isn't that big of a deal.<br>
<br>
At 59 now, I can have as much as 210 wisdom (400 mana difference from 175).  I frequently drop this to as low as 170 to add AC or resists.  These things matter more in a dungeon.  If I am trying to get an evac off or wanting to nuke and then live to tell the tale AC and MR matters.<br>
<br>
In a dungeon, as soon as you start using your mana it is mana flow that matters. Clarity 2, Bard song and so on matter.  As an aside so does HP regen.<br>
<br>
Finally for all matters of power and protection level is far more important. <br>
<br>
When I started, didn't o.d. on base wisdom either.  105.  It simply doesn't matter that much.  I have high agility and str. I don't have to worry too much about carrying things and my AC benefits from agility as well. The differences in base levels amounts to something like a personality difference between players.  It benefits in some ways detracts in others but nothing critical.<br>
<br>
The fun part of the game is not about being invinvcible anyway.  I used to watch my kids when they were around 10 playing video games and getting cheats so they could never loose!!!  How boring, I thought!<br>
<br>
The fun part of the game is having a challenge that is just hard enough that you have to use your wits to win.  Getting the right gear to suit a given situation is part of that. So are tactics.<br>
<br>
Adapting is more valuable than any specific stat as well.<br>
<br>
Fibta, 59 druid quellious<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uainianu.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ainianu</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalWhite.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(5/8/01 7:00:43 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.tripod.co.uk/Aurore/Ainianu.jpg height=280 width=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re: wis</span><hr size=1> 200 wis means practicly nothing imo.<br>
it just means the cap for gaining mana from wisdom (anything over this gives 1 point of mana per point of wisdom)<br>
there is a lot of items which give +mana on it, aswell as ones which give +wisdom, both give you the end result of a 'mana total', that number matters more than your wisdom, i just switch out items over 200wis for ac/hp/mana/resist items since its a waste otherwise.<br>
at lower level's i often had under 200 wis, yet had a much higher mana total than druids that had 200wis and no +mana items, because i was trying to concentrate on my ac/hp at the same time due to the way i was playing and i saw items that gave for example 55mana 55hp and used that instead of a 3wis item, used that kind philosophy a lot and seemed to work well for me. <br>
and also, mana total doesnt mean a thing unless your getting to FM constantly, and in exp groups in dungeons etc that wont happen :p so mana/wis means absolutely nothing there. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utwygg.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Twygg</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(5/8/01 9:47:00 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re: wis</span><hr size=1> Higher wisdom equals greater mana regen and less fizzling which converts to quite a bit more mana over a long period of time.  I normally run with about 199 or 201 wisdom when soloing or doing small groups.  in full resist gear it drops to about 186, but blue diamond gear has so much wisdom on it that you don't lose any mana.<br>
<br>
Aside from fizzling a little more, I notice very little difference between 186 and 201 wisdom for my style of play.  Quad kiters will want to go with as much wisdom as possible though.<br>
<br>
Once you get to a 190ish wisdom, take any upgrades you can get, be it wisdom, ac, hps or resists.  They are all equally important. <p><center><a href="mailto:twygg@prexus.com">Twygg</a> of <a href="http://www.prexus.com/">Prexus</a><br>
60 Heirophant<br>
</center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/umyrtledaturtle.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Myrtle Daturtle</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/ez_icons/emoticons/happy.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(5/10/01 8:31:06 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re: wis</span><hr size=1> You all seem to think along the same lines that your mana pool size is important...mind if I ask why?<br>
<br>
When you are in a group, you're looking to be efficient, not have a large maximum mana value.<br>
<br>
In a group, extra mana in your pool doesn't do much--it gives you the ability to store more mana in your pool.  But what good is free space if it isn't full?<br>
<br>
Fact is, your mana pool is not that important, your mana efficiency is.  A 200 wisdom DOES make you more mana efficient as it ups the probability your specializaiont skill kicking in, hence saving you mana.<br>
<br>
The only real instance I can think of for which a large mana pool would be helpful is when you're attacking a large mob, because you're looking to unload the maximum amount of mana in a limited time.<br>
<br>
But, in general, I find pumping up AC good. <p><table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%"
